To draw a board to show a state of the chessboard in LaTeX using FEN notation, you can use the `chessboard` package. Here is an example of the LaTeX code that does this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

% Define the FEN notation
\def\fenboard{r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n2n2/4P3/2B3P1/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w KQkq - 0 3}

% Draw the board
\setchessboard{setfen=\fenboard}
\chessboard

\end{document}
```

In this code, we first load the `chessboard` package, then define the FEN notation of the chessboard in a macro called `\fenboard`. This macro should contain the FEN string of the chessboard state we want to draw.

Next, we use the `\setchessboard` command to set the chessboard to the FEN notation defined in `\fenboard`. Finally, we use the `\chessboard` command to draw the board.

You can customize the appearance of the board by adjusting the options of the `\setchessboard` command. For example, you can change the size of the board, the color of the squares, and other visual details.

