In Java, the "==" operator is used to compare the references of two objects, while the ".equals()" method is used to compare the values of two objects.

When comparing strings in Java, you should always use the ".equals()" method, not the "==" operator. This is because the "==" operator checks if the two strings are the same object in memory, rather than if they have the same value.

For example, the following code will return true:

String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = "hello";
System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true

However, the following code will return false:

String s3 = new String("hello");
String s4 = "hello";
System.out.println(s3 == s4); // false

This is because s3 is a new String object created in memory, while s4 is a cached String object created by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).

On the other hand, using the ".equals()" method will return true for both cases:

String s5 = new String("hello");
String s6 = "hello";
System.out.println(s5.equals(s6)); // true

In summary, always use the ".equals()" method to compare strings in Java, and avoid using the "==" operator.

